67/* use standard opaque scrollbars for most nodes */
68[data-jp-theme-scrollbars='true'] {
69 scrollbar-color: rgb(var(--jp-scrollbar-thumb-color))
70 var(--jp-scrollbar-background-color);
71}
72
73/* for code nodes, use a transparent style of scrollbar. These selectors
74 * will match lower in the tree, and so will override the above */
75[data-jp-theme-scrollbars='true'] .CodeMirror-hscrollbar,
76[data-jp-theme-scrollbars='true'] .CodeMirror-vscrollbar {
77 scrollbar-color: rgba(var(--jp-scrollbar-thumb-color), 0.5) transparent;
78}
79
80/* tiny scrollbar */
81
82.jp-scrollbar-tiny {
83 scrollbar-color: rgba(var(--jp-scrollbar-thumb-color), 0.5) transparent;
84 scrollbar-width: thin;
85}
86
87/* tiny scrollbar */
88

90.jp-scrollbar-tiny::-webkit-scrollbar-corner {
91 background-color: transparent;
92 height: 4px;
93 width: 4px;
94}
95

98}

6817/*
6818The following CSS variables define the main, public API for styling JupyterLab.
6819These variables should be used by all plugins wherever possible. In other
6820words, plugins should not define custom colors, sizes, etc unless absolutely
6821necessary. This enables users to change the visual theme of JupyterLab
6822by changing these variables.
6823
6824Many variables appear in an ordered sequence (0,1,2,3). These sequences
6825are designed to work well together, so for example, `--jp-border-color1` should
6826be used with `--jp-layout-color1`. The numbers have the following meanings:
6827
6828* 0: super-primary, reserved for special emphasis
6829* 1: primary, most important under normal situations
6830* 2: secondary, next most important under normal situations
6831* 3: tertiary, next most important under normal situations
6832
6833Throughout JupyterLab, we are mostly following principles from Google's
6834Material Design when selecting colors. We are not, however, following
6835all of MD as it is not optimized for dense, information rich UIs.
6836*/
6837
6838:root {

6845 */

7350
7351 function makeMermaidImage(svg) {
7352 const img = document.createElement("img");
7353 const doc = parser.parseFromString(svg, "image/svg+xml");
7354 const svgEl = doc.querySelector("svg");
7355 const { maxWidth } = svgEl?.style || {};
7356 const firstTitle = doc.querySelector("title");
7357 const firstDesc = doc.querySelector("desc");
7358
7359 img.setAttribute("src", `data:image/svg+xml,${encodeURIComponent(svg)}`);
7360 if (maxWidth) {
7361 img.width = parseInt(maxWidth);
7362 }
7363 if (firstTitle) {
7364 img.setAttribute("alt", firstTitle.textContent);
7365 }
7366 if (firstDesc) {
7367 const caption = document.createElement("figcaption");
7368 caption.className = "sr-only";
7369 caption.textContent = firstDesc.textContent;
7370 return [img, caption];
7371 }
7372 return [img];
7373 }
7374
7375 async function makeMermaidError(text) {
7376 let errorMessage = "";
7377 try {
7378 await mermaid.parse(text);
7379 } catch (err) {
7380 errorMessage = `${err}`;
7381 }
7382
7383 const result = document.createElement("details");
7384 result.className = 'jp-RenderedMermaid-Details';
7385 const summary = document.createElement("summary");
7386 summary.className = 'jp-RenderedMermaid-Summary';
7387 const pre = document.createElement("pre");
7388 const code = document.createElement("code");
7389 code.innerText = text;
7390 pre.appendChild(code);
7391 summary.appendChild(pre);
7392 result.appendChild(summary);
7393
7394 const warning = document.createElement("pre");
7395 warning.innerText = errorMessage;
7396 result.appendChild(warning);
7397 return [result];
7398 }
7399
7400 async function renderOneMarmaid(src) {
7401 const id = `jp-mermaid-${_nextMermaidId++}`;
7402 const parent = src.parentNode;
7403 let raw = src.textContent.trim();
7404 const el = document.createElement("div");
7405 el.style.visibility = "hidden";
7406 document.body.appendChild(el);
7407 let results = null;
7408 let output = null;
7409 try {
7410 let { svg } = await mermaid.render(id, raw, el);
7411 svg = cleanMermaidSvg(svg);
7412 results = makeMermaidImage(svg);
7413 output = document.createElement("figure");
7414 results.map(output.appendChild, output);
7415 } catch (err) {
7416 parent.classList.add("jp-mod-warning");
7417 results = await makeMermaidError(raw);
7418 output = results[0];
7419 } finally {
7420 el.remove();
7421 }
7422 parent.classList.add("jp-RenderedMermaid");
7423 parent.appendChild(output);
7424 }
7425
7426
7427 /**
7428 * Post-process to ensure mermaid diagrams contain only valid SVG and XHTML.
7429 */
7430 function cleanMermaidSvg(svg) {
7431 return svg.replace(RE_VOID_ELEMENT, replaceVoidElement);
7432 }
7433
7434
7435 /**
7436 * A regular expression for all void elements, which may include attributes and
7437 * a slash.
7438 *
7439 * @see https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Glossary/Void_element
7440 *
7441 * Of these, only `<br>` is generated by Mermaid in place of `\n`,
7442 * but _any_ "malformed" tag will break the SVG rendering entirely.
7443 */
7444 const RE_VOID_ELEMENT =
7445 /<\s*(area|base|br|col|embed|hr|img|input|link|meta|param|source|track|wbr)\s*([^>]*?)\s*>/gi;
7446
7447 /**
7448 * Ensure a void element is closed with a slash, preserving any attributes.
7449 */
7450 function replaceVoidElement(match, tag, rest) {
7451 rest = rest.trim();
7452 if (!rest.endsWith('/')) {
7453 rest = `${rest} /`;
7454 }
7455 return `<${tag} ${rest}>`;
7456 }
7457
7458 void Promise.all([...diagrams].map(renderOneMarmaid));
7459 });
7460</script>

7519<h2 id="OCIO-and-MaterialX">OCIO and MaterialX<a class="anchor-link" href="#OCIO-and-MaterialX"></a></h2><p>This notebook will cover one workflow of using OCIO to generate code for MaterialX.
7520We will be using the API based on OCIO 2.2 and above (released in October 2022).</p>
7521<p>The aim of this notebook is to go over how OCIO can be used to generate "implementations".
7522The longer term MaterialX aim is to generate functional node graphs. This book will cover the setup required for generation, but can only show how source code implementation generation can be performed at the curren time.</p>
7523<p>The workflow covered is the "green" parts in this overall workflow diagram:
7524<img alt="No description has been provided for this image" src="./images/OCIO_MaterialX_Workflow.png"/></p>
7525<p>If / when graph generation is possible source code implementations can be swapped out for graph implementations.</p>
7526<p>The breakdown is as follows:
7527library (<code>cmlib</code>)</p>
7528<ol>
7529<li>OCIO setup</li>
7530<li>Setting up OCIO configurations and getting available color spaces.</li>
7531<li>Setting up OCIO "processors" for generating color transforms</li>
7532<li>Generating source code implementations</li>
7533<li>Creating MaterialX implementations and definition wrappers for <code>color3</code> and <code>color4</code> variants.</li>
7534<li>Add definitions and implementations to the "standard" transform</li>
7535</ol>
7536<p>For further OCI there is a fair bit of documentation available with a useful starting place <a href="https://opencolorio.readthedocs.io/en/latest/guides/developing/developing.html">here</a></p>
7537</div>
7538</div>
7539</div>

7547<h3 id="Setup">Setup<a class="anchor-link" href="#Setup"></a></h3><p>OpenColorIO is available as a pre-built Python package on PyPi <a href="https://pypi.org/project/opencolorio/">here</a></p>
7548<p><code>pip</code> can be used to install the package which is called <code>PyOpenColorIO</code></p>
7549<p>User can also build OpenColorIO by cloning the <a href="https://github.com/AcademySoftwareFoundation/OpenColorIO/">GitHub repository</a>.</p>
7550<p>For the purposes of generating color transform implementation, most of the build options can be disabled. For For building and installing the Python package, make sure that the appropriate build option is set (current <code>OCIO_BUILD_PYTHON</code>, <code>OCIO_INSTALL_EXT_PACKAGES</code> respectively).</p>
7551<p>An example set of options is given here:</p>
7552<pre><code>-DOPENIMAGEIO_INCLUDE_DIR="" -DOPENIMAGEIO_LIBRARY="" -DOCIO_BUILD_DOCS=OFF -DBUILD_SHARED_LIBS=OFF -DOCIO_BUILD_TESTS=ON -DOCIO_BUILD_GPU_TESTS=OFF -DOCIO_BUILD_PYTHON=1 -DOCIO_BUILD_JAVA=0 -DOCIO_INSTALL_EXT_PACKAGES=ALL -DOCIO_BUILD_APPS=0 -DOCIO_BUILD_NUKE=0
7553</code></pre>
7554<p>A third alternative is to use a pre-built Python package which comes with another installation such as a DCC. A check should be made to not inadvertently use the incorrect version of the package.</p>
7555<p>For this book, we install from PyPi.</p>
7556</div>

7625<h3 id="Configurations">Configurations<a class="anchor-link" href="#Configurations"></a></h3><p>As of version 2.2, <code>ACES Cg Config</code> and <code>ACES Studio Config</code> are packaged with <code>OCIO</code>, meaning that they are available to use without having to download them separately. The <code>getBuildInConfigs()</code> API is explained <a href="https://opencolorio.readthedocs.io/en/latest/releases/ocio_2_2.html">here</a></p>

8101</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
8102<h3 id="Supported-Color-Spaces-in-MaterialX">Supported Color Spaces in MaterialX<a class="anchor-link" href="#Supported-Color-Spaces-in-MaterialX"></a></h3><p>MaterialX currently uses color space names for :</p>
8103<ol>
8104<li>Color space (<code>colorspace</code> attribute) tagging for input images (<code>filename</code> attributes) and colors (<code>color3</code> and <code>color4</code> types).</li>
8105<li>Node category identifiers for node definitions of the form <code>&lt;from color space&gt;_&lt;to color space name&gt;</code> to specify color space conversion nodes. (Node definitions are support as of MaterialX 1.38.7)</li>
8106</ol>
8107<p>Note that any valid color space name can be used for input tagging.</p>
8108<p>At time of writing only specific color space conversions are supported via node definitions and hence can perform code injection during shader code generation.
8109Any color space information can still be passed as meta-data to the code generated (e.g. as is possible with the <code>OSL</code> generator).</p>
8110<p>Further note that only certain <strong>aliases</strong> which are valid MaterialX identifiers are recognized in this context. For example <code>g18_rec709</code> is used for color space <code>Gamma 1.8 Rec.709 - Texture</code> and <code>lin_rec709</code> is used for color space <code>Linear Rec.709 (sRGB)</code>.</p>
8111</div>
8112</div>
8113</div>
8114</div>
8115<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
8116<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
8117<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
8118</div>
8119<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
8120</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
8121<h3 id="OCIO-Shader-Code-Generation">OCIO Shader Code Generation<a class="anchor-link" href="#OCIO-Shader-Code-Generation"></a></h3><p>It is possible to generate code color space transforms for certain code generation targets.</p>
8122<p>This is done by:</p>
8123<ol>
8124<li>Calling <code>getProcessor()</code> on the config with desired "source" and "destination" color spaces for the transform.</li>
8125<li>Creating a CPU or GPU processor</li>
8126<li>Set the appropriate target language</li>
8127<li>Getting the shader code using <code>getShaderText()</code></li>
8128</ol>
8129</div>
8130</div>
8131</div>
8132</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell">
8133<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
8134<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
8135</div>
8136<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">
8137<div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">In[]:</div>
8138<div class="jp-CodeMirrorEditor jp-Editor jp-InputArea-editor" data-type="inline">
8139<div class="cm-editor cm-s-jupyter">
8140<div class="highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">generateShaderCode</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">config</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sourceColorSpace</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">destColorSpace</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">language</span><span class="p">):</span>
8141 <span class="n">cshaderCodee</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">''</span>

8149 <span class="k">except</span><span class="p">:</span>
8150 <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">shaderCode</span>
8151

8153 <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">processor</span><span class="p">:</span>
8154 <span class="n">gpuProcessor</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">processor</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">getDefaultGPUProcessor</span><span class="p">()</span>

8160 <span class="n">shaderCode</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">shaderDesc</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">getShaderText</span><span class="p">()</span>
8161
8162 <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">shaderCode</span>
8163
8164<span class="c1"># Use GLSL as the shader language to produce, and linear as the target color space</span>
8165<span class="n">language</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">OCIO</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">GpuLanguage</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">GPU_LANGUAGE_GLSL_4_0</span>
8166<span class="n">targetColorSpace</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">'lin_rec709'</span>
8167
8168<span class="c1"># Go through all the config and create code for each transform</span>
8169
8170<span class="n">title</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">'| Source | Target | Code |</span><span class="se">\n</span><span class="s1">'</span>

8172
8173<span class="n">rows</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">''</span>
8174<span class="n">testedSources</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="nb">set</span><span class="p">()</span>
8175<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">c</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">configs</span><span class="p">:</span>
8176 <span class="n">config</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">OCIO</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Config</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">CreateFromBuiltinConfig</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">c</span><span class="p">)</span>

8433<h3 id="Integrating-OCIO-with-MaterialX">Integrating OCIO with MaterialX<a class="anchor-link" href="#Integrating-OCIO-with-MaterialX"></a></h3><p>We will pick an example transform to go over details on mapping from OCIO to MaterialX.</p>
8434<p>The first thing of note is OCIO function signatures</p>
8435<ul>
8436<li><p>Currently all signatures transform 4 channel color inputs while MaterialX supports both 3 and 4 channel variants. This can be easily handled by adding pre and post conversion nodes, or by creating variant function signatures. The former is more robust and more in line with the proposed direction to have all OCIO transforms to be represented as graphs.</p>
8437</li>
8438<li><p>The signature name is not unique. This can be handled as OCIO provides mechanism to override the function names using <code>setFunctionName</code> and <code>setResourcePrefix</code>.</p>
8439</li>
8440</ul>
8441<p>Following the current MaterialX convention we use the signature notation:
8442<code>mx_&lt;sourceName&gt;_to_&lt;targetname&gt;_&lt;type&gt;</code> where <code>type</code> is either <code>color3</code> or <code>color4</code> for 3 or 4 channel variants.</p>
8443</div>
8444</div>
8445</div>
8446</div>
8447<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
8448<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
8449<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
8450</div>
8451<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
8452</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
8453<p>We add in two new utilities:</p>
8454<ol>
8455<li><code>createTransformName</code> which will generate the unique function name</li>
8456<li><code>setShaderDescriptionParameters</code> which overrides the function name but also adds a prefix to uniquely identify dependent resources.</li>
8457</ol>
8458<p>These are then used in a new code generation variation called <code>generateShaderCode2()</code> which has additionally been modified to return the number of dependent texture resources, which can be queried from the shader
8459descriptor via the <code>GpuShaderDesc.getTextures()</code> iterator.</p>
8460</div>
8461</div>
8462</div>
8463</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell jp-mod-noOutputs">
8464<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
8465<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
8466</div>
8467<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea">

8523<h3 id="OCIO-Resource-Dependencies">OCIO Resource Dependencies<a class="anchor-link" href="#OCIO-Resource-Dependencies"></a></h3><p>Resource dependencies is a second major issue to examine.</p>
8524<p>In the example below we convert two different source color spaces.</p>
8525<p>One is "self-contained" in that there are no support functions being produced (<code>ACES2065-1</code>),
8526while the second adds additional function and resources. Note that we maintain uniqueness of these additions by using <code>setFunctionName</code> and <code>setResourcePrefix</code> respectively.</p>
8527<h4 id="Example-1:-Self-contained">Example 1: Self-contained<a class="anchor-link" href="#Example-1:-Self-contained"></a></h4>
8528</div>
8529</div>

8540<span class="n">textureCount</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>
8541<span class="n">code</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">''</span>
8542<span class="n">code</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">textureCount</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">generateShaderCode2</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">builtinCfgC</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">sourceColorSpace</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">targetColorSpace</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">language</span><span class="p">)</span>

8703</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
8704<h4 id="Issues-With-Texture-Resources">Issues With Texture Resources<a class="anchor-link" href="#Issues-With-Texture-Resources"></a></h4><p>From an integration point of view any introduction of texture lookups requires resource declarations in the code. (such as the <code>uniform sampler2D mx_ACEScc_to_lin_rec709_color4_ocio_lut1d_0Sampler;</code> sampler declaration).</p>
8705<ol>
8706<li><p>The only way to handle these is to have additional logic added for code insertion of color transforms, such that the shader function declarations and resources can be inserted into the code independently. The current MaterialX code generation logic does not otherwise support this using the "default color system".</p>
8707<blockquote>
8708<p>Note : An experiment was attempted previously but does not align with the current proposal to have stand-alone node definitions. It was thus abandoned. ( For those interested the full code with code changes can be found <a href="https://github.com/autodesk-forks/MaterialX/pull/1379/files#diff-a181860f6edce31fab2f260d982a9363ef80062b7eea99f63a19cf0ea60ee44f">here</a>). Here 1D lookups (LUTS) were specified as input arrays and code generation created 1D textures dynamically based on the array inputs. 3D lookups were not handled.</p>
8709</blockquote>
8710</li>
8711<li><p><strong>From the point of view of creating node graphs, any implementation resource dependencies means it cannot be cleanly wrapped up into a self-contained node definition and implementation.</strong></p>
8712</li>
8713</ol>
8714<p>For now these can be "skipped" until such time as they are require, or the implementation changes
8715to avoid using these.</p>
8716</div>
8717</div>
8718</div>
8719</div>

8727the following code.</p>

8730reuse the existing utility <code>generateShaderCode2</code>).</p>

8788<h3 id="Target-Language-Support">Target Language Support<a class="anchor-link" href="#Target-Language-Support"></a></h3><p>At time of writing the target languages supported by OCIO and MaterialX differ. This includes non-core support such as <code>MDL</code> and current versions of <code>OSL</code>. Also as no logical operators are provided as with MaterialX, targets such as <code>Vex</code> which parses and maps MaterialX nodes as operators is not easy to do.</p>
8789<p>OCIO and MaterialX recently added in <code>Metal</code> language support. It is to be checked if there would be any issues with the additional <code>struct</code> wrappers required for this language as it is uncommon for MaterialX code generation to call into a <code>struct</code> function at the current time.</p>
8790</div>
8791</div>

8872<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
8873</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
8874<p>Using version 2.3 to access <code>OSL</code> there appears to be additional issues with the code
8875generated as additional utility functions may be inserted which are not renamed to avoid collisions.</p>
8876<p>For example functions called <code>max()</code>, <code>pow()</code> etc are added which are outside the scope of the main shader declaration for which do not seem to be included in the logic for unique function name. As well as include additional include files which should be part of the OSL distribution. These need to be stripped out to embed this code as part of a larger OSL shader which already includes these functions to avoid name clashes.
8877An <a href="https://github.com/AcademySoftwareFoundation/OpenColorIO/issues/1851" target="_blank">issue</a> has been logged for this.</p>
8878<p>As <code>OSL</code> integrations will generally perform color management outside of the shader, it is to be seen if this is important enough to address.</p>

9004<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
9005</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
9006<h3 id="Creating-MaterialX-Node-Definitions-/-Implementation">Creating MaterialX Node Definitions / Implementation<a class="anchor-link" href="#Creating-MaterialX-Node-Definitions-/-Implementation"></a></h3><p>Given source code for now, it is still possible to create implementations and node definitions. If in the future
9007the implementations can become MaterialX node graphs then the definition interface can still be used.</p>
9008<p>To create a new definition:</p>
9009<ol>
9010<li>The source and target color space is used to derive:<ul>
9011<li>a transform name: using the previously described <code>createTransformName()</code> utility</li>
9012<li>a node name by replace the 'mx_' function name with the "standard" 'ND_' prefix used for definition</li>
9013<li>a node category</li>
9014</ul>
9015</li>
9016<li>Use <code>addNodeDef()</code> API to add a new definition</li>
9017<li>Set node group to be <code>colortransform</code> which is the recommended group for new color transforms.</li>
9018<li>Add a single input and output of the appropriate type (<code>color3</code> or <code>color4</code>).</li>
9019<li>Set a default value on the input. For this code we assume the defaul to be opaque black.</li>
9020</ol>
9021<p>Thie logic is encapsulated in a new <code>generateMaterialXDefinition()</code> utility function.</p>
9022</div>
9023</div>
9024</div>
9025</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell jp-mod-noOutputs">
9026<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">

9028</div>

9038

Generated via OCIO. '</span> <span class="o">%</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">sourceColorSpace</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">targetColorSpace</span><span class="p">))</span>
9041

9043 <span class="n">category</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sourceColorSpace</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="s1">'_to_'</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">targetColorSpace</span>
9044 <span class="n">definition</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">setNodeString</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">category</span><span class="p">)</span>
9045 <span class="n">definition</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">setNodeGroup</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'colortransform'</span><span class="p">)</span>
9046
9047 <span class="n">defaultValueString</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">'0.0 0.0 0.0 1.0'</span>
9048 <span class="n">defaultValue</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mx</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">createValueFromStrings</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">defaultValueString</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'color4'</span><span class="p">)</span>
9049 <span class="nb">input</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">definition</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">addInput</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">inputName</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="nb">type</span><span class="p">)</span>

9067<p>Another utility called <code>writeShaderCode()</code> is used to write the code to file following the "standard" MaterialX naming convention.</p>

9093<div class="jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
9094<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">

9098</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
9099<p>The implementation creation logic is encapsulated in a <code>createMaterialXImplementation()</code> utility function which appends a new implementation to an existing Document.</p>
9100<p>The transform name is assumged to be precreated using <code>createTransformName()</code>.</p>
9101<p>This is used to create a unique implementation Element name, and source code filename. We decied to use a file on disk as it is not possible to inline 1 or more function functions created by OCIO.</p>
9102<p>The implementation is associated with an existing node definition which is passed in and a target is explicit set to indicate which shading language (target) the implementation is for.</p>
9103</div>

9113<div class="cm-editor cm-s-jupyter">
9114<div class="highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">createMaterialXImplementation</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">doc</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">definition</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">transformName</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">extension</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">target</span><span class="p">):</span>
9115<span class="w"> </span><span class="sd">'''</span>
9116<span class="sd"> Create a new implementation in a document for a given definition.</span>
9117<span class="sd"> '''</span>
9118 <span class="n">implName</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">transformName</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="s1">'_'</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">target</span>
9119 <span class="n">filename</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">transformName</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="s1">'.'</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">extension</span>
9120 <span class="n">implName</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">implName</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">replace</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'mx_'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'IM_'</span><span class="p">)</span>
9121
9122 <span class="c1"># Check if implementation already exists</span>
9123 <span class="n">impl</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">doc</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">getImplementation</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">implName</span><span class="p">)</span>
9124 <span class="k">if</span> <span class="n">impl</span><span class="p">:</span>
9125 <span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Implementation already exists: </span><span class="si">%s</span><span class="s1">'</span> <span class="o">%</span> <span class="n">implName</span><span class="p">)</span>
9126 <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">impl</span>
9127
9128 <span class="n">comment</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">doc</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">addChildOfCategory</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'comment'</span><span class="p">)</span>
9129 <span class="n">comment</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">setDocString</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">' Color space </span><span class="si">%s</span><span class="s1"> to </span><span class="si">%s</span><span class="s1"> transform. Generated via OCIO for target: </span><span class="si">%s</span><span class="s1">'</span>
9130 <span class="o">%</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">sourceColorSpace</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">targetColorSpace</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">target</span><span class="p">))</span>
9131 <span class="n">impl</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">doc</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">addImplementation</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">implName</span><span class="p">)</span>
9132 <span class="n">impl</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">setFile</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">filename</span><span class="p">)</span>
9133 <span class="n">impl</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">setFunction</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">transformName</span><span class="p">)</span>
9134 <span class="n">impl</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">setTarget</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">target</span><span class="p">)</span>
9135 <span class="n">impl</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">setNodeDef</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">definition</span><span class="p">)</span>
9136
9137 <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">impl</span>
9138</pre></div>
9139</div>
9140</div>
9141</div>
9142</div>
9143</div>

9149</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
9150<p>Finally a small utility is added to write the document to disk.</p>

9162<div class="highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">writeDocument</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">doc</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">filename</span><span class="p">):</span>
9163 <span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Write MaterialX file:'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">filename</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">asString</span><span class="p">())</span>
9164 <span class="n">mx</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">writeToXmlFile</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">doc</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">filename</span><span class="p">)</span>

9172<div class="jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex="0">
9173<div class="jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
9174</div>
9175<div class="jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class="jp-InputPrompt jp-InputArea-prompt">
9176</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput" data-mime-type="text/markdown">
9177<p>Using these utilities we:</p>
9178<ul>
9179<li>Create separate definition and implementation Documents.</li>
9180<li>Generate shader code for <code>GLSL</code>, <code>MSL</code>, and <code>OSL`` for the same color transform. (</code>OSL` is available in version 2.3).</li>
9181<li>Create a new definition for that transform</li>
9182<li>Create a new implementation for each shader code result</li>
9183</ul>
9184</div>
9185</div>
9186</div>
9187</div><div class="jp-Cell jp-CodeCell jp-Notebook-cell">

9196<span class="c1"># - source code for a given transform for 2 shader targets</span>
9197<span class="c1"># - A definition wrapper for the source</span>
9198<span class="c1"># - An implementations per source code. All implementations are associated with single definition</span>
9199<span class="n">definitionDoc</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mx</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">createDocument</span><span class="p">()</span>

9201

9222 <span class="n">generationList</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="s1">'genosl'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'osl'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">OCIO</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">GpuLanguage</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">LANGUAGE_OSL_1</span><span class="p">])</span>

9351<h3 id="Variant-Creation">Variant Creation<a class="anchor-link" href="#Variant-Creation"></a></h3><p>Given a node definition for the <code>color4</code> variant is is possible to create a functional graph and corresponding definition for a <code>color3</code> variant. The graph simple convertes from <code>color3</code> to <code>color4</code> before connecting to the transform and then converts back to <code>color3</code> for output.</p>

9456<h3 id="MaterialX-Standard-Library-Inclusion">MaterialX Standard Library Inclusion<a class="anchor-link" href="#MaterialX-Standard-Library-Inclusion"></a></h3><p>It is possible to add a new color space transform to the "standard" MaterialX library locations. This can be done for local testing for in some cases when additional search paths are not supported.</p>
9457<p>Introduced with version <strong>1.38.7</strong>, the location of definitions and implementations can be found in the <code>cmlib</code> folder under the installation <code>libraries</code> location. Note that target specific source file directories were removed as all implementations are now target independent node graphs.</p>
9458<p>To include source file implementations the appropriate <code>target</code> folders can be added in.
9459Under that folder an implementation file can be added for each target along with associated source files. The new definition can be added to `cmlib_defs.mtlx.</p>
9460<p>See the <a href="mtlx_definitions_notebook.html" target="_blank">Creating Definitions</a> book for more on how set up new definitions.</p>
9461<p>The standard library folder structure is partially shown below. The bolded items would be the ones of interest. The <code>stdlib</code> folder is also shown to show how each folder follows the same naming and hierarchy conventions.</p>
9462<hr/>
9463<ul>
9464<li>cmlib // Color space transform library<ul>
9465<li><strong>cmlib_defs.mtlx</strong> // definitions file</li>
9466<li>cmlib_ng.mtlx // functional node graphs file</li>
9467<li><strong>genglsl</strong> // GLSL implementation folder<ul>
9468<li><strong>cmlib_genglsl_impl.mtlx</strong> // Implementation declarations</li>
9469<li><strong>GLSL files reside here</strong></li>
9470</ul>
9471</li>
9472<li><strong>genmsl</strong> // MSL implementation folder<ul>
9473<li><strong>cmlib_genmsl_impl.mtlx</strong> // Implementation declarations</li>
9474<li><strong>MSL files reside here</strong></li>
9475</ul>
9476</li>
9477</ul>
9478</li>
9479<li>stdlib // "Standard" node library<ul>
9480<li>genglsl<ul>
9481<li>stdlib_genglsl_impl.mtlx</li>
9482</ul>
9483</li>
9484<li>genmdl</li>
9485<li>genmsl<ul>
9486<li>stdlib_genmsl_impl.mtlx</li>
9487</ul>
9488</li>
9489<li>genosl</li>
9490<li>targets</li>
9491</ul>
9492</li>
9493</ul>

9505<h3 id="Future-Exploration">Future Exploration<a class="anchor-link" href="#Future-Exploration"></a></h3><p>As mentioned the notion of representing OCIO shader logic as MaterialX nodes is still under discussion.
9506There are thoughts to try and export each lower level functional "block" as a reusable functions with the appripriate argument values, hence allowing for a custom OCIO code generator to emit a new MaterialX node for each function.</p>
9507<p>At time of writing the ASWF OCIO techincal steering committee (TSC) additionally has on it's roadmap to reduce the size of OCIO and consider how it could be deployed in a Web or mobile environment. Here it is possible to consider both a source code or a node graph based option. The latter could fit in with the interest to transport some subset of MaterialX via formats such as <code>glTF</code>.</p>
